    <title>Combined summary - Proposal: Package Mempool Accept and Package RBF</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T02:19:16.458278+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2021-September/019464.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin Core developer Gloria Zhao has proposed changes to the mempool policy in Bitcoin Core. The proposed changes aim to optimize the validation and propagation of transactions, make fee-bumping tools more powerful for users, and provide greater security for applications and users relying on time-sensitive transactions. The changes include allowing packages consisting of multiple parents and one child, and using the total package feerate instead of the individual feerate to meet the two feerate requirements of a mempool. The proposal also includes several key points such as allowing packages that may contain already-in-mempool transactions and using "package RBF" as a new method to replace-by-fee transactions.The proposal represents an effort to improve the functionality and usability of the Bitcoin network while maintaining its security and decentralization. The group debates the logical order of the checks and whether only the package RBF should apply. Limitations on topology are also discussed, with some suggesting a conservative approach of deploying during a first phase 1-parent/1-child. The proposed policy would allow for packages consisting of multiple parents and one child to be validated together, enabling more effective fee-bumping tools for users relying on time-sensitive transactions. The proposal also introduces the concept of Package Mempool Accept, which includes changes to mempool validation logic, policy, and transaction relay to better propagate transactions with the highest package feerates to miners. The proposed package RBF rule utilizes the fees and size of the entire package, and this can be pretty high if there are potential conflicts with other commitment transactions. There are discussions on potential attacks on commitment transactions from different channels by blocking them under a high-fee child. Additionally, there is a debate on whether to accept a package with lower feerate if an individual transaction in the package has a higher feerate. Some concerns are raised about the potential risks of using packages to fee-bump replaceable transactions, such as Lightning Network commitments.The bitcoin-dev mailing list is discussing a proposed package replace-by-fee (RBF) logic for Bitcoin transactions. The proposal includes various checks such as topological sorting, no conflicting transactions, and a specific topology of one child with all its unconfirmed parents. The proposal aims to improve the efficiency and security of the Bitcoin network's mempool while allowing for greater flexibility for users and applications like Lightning.Finally, the Bitcoin Core team has proposed changes to the default transaction relay policy in order to improve the privacy of Bitcoin users. These changes are based on BIP-125, which outlines a new transaction relay protocol that improves privacy by randomizing the order in which transactions are relayed. Additionally, the changes aim to reduce the impact of spam attacks on the network by introducing limits on the number of low-fee transactions that can be included in a block.</summary>
